[src:service-mesh-deep/load-balancing-computing] Numerous scheduling algorithms, also called load-balancing methods, are used by load balancers to determine which back-end server to send a request to.
[src:service-mesh-deep/load-balancing-computing] Simple algorithms include random choice, round robin, or least connections.
[src:service-mesh-deep/load-balancing-computing] An important issue when operating a load-balanced service is how to handle information that must be kept across the multiple requests in a user's session.
[src:service-mesh-deep/load-balancing-computing] If this information is stored locally on one backend server, then subsequent requests going to different backend servers would not be able to find it.
[src:service-mesh-deep/load-balancing-computing] This might be cached information that can be recomputed, in which case load-balancing a request to a different backend server just introduces a performance issue.
[src:service-mesh-deep/load-balancing-computing] Ideally, the cluster of servers behind the load balancer should not be session-aware, so that if a client connects to any backend server at any time the user experience is unaffected.
[src:service-mesh-deep/load-balancing-computing] This is usually achieved with a shared database or an in-memory session database like Memcached.
[src:service-mesh-deep/load-balancing-computing] One basic solution to the session data issue is to send all requests in a user session consistently to the same backend server.
[src:service-mesh-deep/load-balancing-computing] This is known as "persistence" or "stickiness".
[src:service-mesh-deep/load-balancing-computing] A significant downside to this technique is its lack of automatic failover: if a backend server goes down, its per-session information becomes inaccessible, and any sessions depending on it are lost.
[src:service-mesh-deep/load-balancing-computing] The same problem is usually relevant to central database servers; even if web servers are "stateless" and not "sticky", the central database is (see below).
[src:service-mesh-deep/load-balancing-computing] Assignment to a particular server might be based on a username, client IP address, or random.
[src:service-mesh-deep/load-balancing-computing] Because of changes in the client's perceived address resulting from DHCP, network address translation, and web proxies this method may be unreliable.
[src:service-mesh-deep/load-balancing-computing] Random assignments must be remembered by the load balancer, which creates a burden on storage.
[src:service-mesh-deep/load-balancing-computing] If the load balancer is replaced or fails, this information may be lost, and assignments may need to be deleted after a timeout period or during periods of high load to avoid exceeding the space available for the assignment table.
[src:service-mesh-deep/load-balancing-computing] The random assignment method also requires that clients maintain some state, which can be a problem, for example when a web browser has disabled the storage of cookies.
[src:service-mesh-deep/load-balancing-computing] Sophisticated load balancers use multiple persistence techniques to avoid some of the shortcomings of any one method.
[src:service-mesh-deep/load-balancing-computing] Another solution is to keep the per-session data in a database.
[src:service-mesh-deep/load-balancing-computing] This can reduce performance because it increases the load on the database: the database is best used to store information less transient than per-session data.
[src:service-mesh-deep/load-balancing-computing] To prevent a database from becoming a single point of failure, and to improve scalability, the database is often replicated across multiple machines, and load balancing is used to spread the query load across those replicas.
[src:service-mesh-deep/load-balancing-computing] Microsoft's ASP.net State Server technology is an example of a session database.
[src:service-mesh-deep/load-balancing-computing] All servers in a web farm store their session data on State Server and any server in the farm can retrieve the data.
[src:service-mesh-deep/load-balancing-computing] When the client is a web browser, one approach is to store the per-session data in the browser itself.
[src:service-mesh-deep/load-balancing-computing] One way to achieve this is to use a browser cookie, suitably time-stamped and encrypted.
[src:service-mesh-deep/load-balancing-computing] Storing session data on the client is generally the preferred solution: then the load balancer is free to pick any backend server to handle a request.
[src:service-mesh-deep/load-balancing-computing] However, this method of state-data handling may be unsuitable for some complex business logic scenarios, where the session state payload is large and recomputing it with every request on a server is not feasible.
