[src:service-mesh-deep/load-balancing-computing] Firewalls can prevent direct connections to backend servers, for network security reasons.
[src:service-mesh-deep/load-balancing-computing] Intrusion prevention systems offer application layer security in addition to the network/transport layer offered by firewall security.
[src:service-mesh-deep/load-balancing-computing] Load balancing can be useful in applications with redundant communications links.
[src:service-mesh-deep/load-balancing-computing] For example, a company may have multiple Internet connections ensuring network access if one of the connections fails.
[src:service-mesh-deep/load-balancing-computing] A failover arrangement would mean that one link is designated for normal use, while the second link is used only if the primary link fails.
[src:service-mesh-deep/load-balancing-computing] Using load balancing, both links can be in use all the time.
[src:service-mesh-deep/load-balancing-computing] A device or program monitors the availability of all links and selects the path for sending packets.
[src:service-mesh-deep/load-balancing-computing] The use of multiple links simultaneously increases the available bandwidth.
[src:service-mesh-deep/load-balancing-computing] TRILL (Transparent Interconnection of Lots of Links) facilitates an Ethernet to have an arbitrary topology, and enables per flow pair-wise load splitting by way of Dijkstra's algorithm, without configuration and user intervention.
[src:service-mesh-deep/load-balancing-computing] The catalyst for TRILL was an event at Beth Israel Deaconess Medical Center which began on 13 November 2002.
[src:service-mesh-deep/load-balancing-computing] The concept of Rbridges [sic] was first proposed to the Institute of Electrical and Electronics Engineers in the year 2004, whom in 2005 rejected what came to be known as TRILL, and in the years 2006 through 2012 devised an incompatible variation known as Shortest Path Bridging.
[src:service-mesh-deep/load-balancing-computing] The IEEE approved the IEEE 802.1aq standard in May 2012, also known as Shortest Path Bridging (SPB).
[src:service-mesh-deep/load-balancing-computing] SPB allows all links to be active through multiple equal-cost paths, provides faster convergence times to reduce downtime, and simplifies the use of load balancing in mesh network topologies (partially connected and/or fully connected) by allowing traffic to load share across all paths of a network.
[src:service-mesh-deep/load-balancing-computing] SPB is designed to reduce configuration errors and preserves the plug-and-play nature that established Ethernet as the de facto protocol at Layer 2.
[src:service-mesh-deep/load-balancing-computing] Many telecommunications companies have multiple routes through their networks or to external networks.
[src:service-mesh-deep/load-balancing-computing] They use sophisticated load balancing to shift traffic from one path to another to avoid network congestion on any particular link, and sometimes to minimize the cost of transit across external networks or improve network reliability.
[src:service-mesh-deep/load-balancing-computing] Another way of using load balancing is in network monitoring activities.
[src:service-mesh-deep/load-balancing-computing] Load balancers can be used to split huge data flows into several sub-flows and use several network analyzers, each reading a part of the original data.
[src:service-mesh-deep/load-balancing-computing] This can be used for monitoring fast networks like 10GbE or STM64, where complex processing of the data may not be possible at wire speed.
[src:service-mesh-deep/load-balancing-computing] Load balancing is widely used in data center networks to distribute traffic across many existing paths between any two servers.
[src:service-mesh-deep/load-balancing-computing] It allows more efficient use of network bandwidth and reduces provisioning costs.
[src:service-mesh-deep/load-balancing-computing] In general, load balancing in datacenter networks can be classified as either static or dynamic.
[src:service-mesh-deep/load-balancing-computing] Static load balancing distributes traffic by computing a hash of the source and destination addresses and port numbers of traffic flows and using it to determine how flows are assigned to one of the existing paths.
[src:service-mesh-deep/load-balancing-computing] Dynamic load balancing assigns traffic flows to paths by monitoring bandwidth use on different paths.
[src:service-mesh-deep/load-balancing-computing] Dynamic assignments can also be proactive or reactive.
[src:service-mesh-deep/load-balancing-computing] In the former case, the assignment is fixed once made, while in the latter the network logic keeps monitoring available paths and shifts flows across them as network utilization changes (with arrival of new flows or completion of existing ones).
[src:service-mesh-deep/load-balancing-computing] A comprehensive overview of load balancing in datacenter networks has been made available.
[src:service-mesh-deep/load-balancing-computing] Load balancing is often used to implement failover—the continuation of service after the failure of one or more of its components.
[src:service-mesh-deep/load-balancing-computing] The components are monitored continually (e.g., web servers may be monitored by fetching known pages), and when one becomes unresponsive, the load balancer is informed and no longer sends traffic to it.
[src:service-mesh-deep/load-balancing-computing] When a component comes back online, the load balancer starts rerouting traffic to it.
[src:service-mesh-deep/load-balancing-computing] For this to work, there must be at least one component in excess of the service's capacity (N+1 redundancy).
[src:service-mesh-deep/load-balancing-computing] This can be much less expensive and more flexible than failover approaches where every single live component is paired with a single backup component that takes over in the event of a failure (dual modular redundancy).
[src:service-mesh-deep/load-balancing-computing] Some RAID systems can also utilize hot spare for a similar effect.
[src:service-mesh-deep/load-balancing-computing] This technique can increase fault tolerance by enabling quick substitutions for the most complicated, most failure-prone parts of a system.
[src:service-mesh-deep/load-balancing-computing] However, it can make the load balancer itself a single point of failure.
[src:service-mesh-deep/load-balancing-computing] To maintain the necessary high throughput and low latency, organizations commonly deploy load balancing tools capable of advanced TCP optimizations, connection pooling, and adaptive scheduling.
[src:service-mesh-deep/load-balancing-computing] Such features help distribute incoming data requests evenly across servers or nodes, prevent congestion, and ensure that compute resources remain efficiently utilized.
[src:service-mesh-deep/load-balancing-computing] When deployed in large-scale or high-performance AI environments, load balancers also mitigate bandwidth constraints and accommodate varying data governance requirements—particularly when sensitive training data cannot be sent to third-party cloud services.
[src:service-mesh-deep/load-balancing-computing] By routing data locally (on-premises) or across private clouds, load balancers allow AI workflows to avoid public-cloud bandwidth limits, reduce transit costs, and maintain compliance with regulatory standards.
[src:service-mesh-deep/load-balancing-computing] As AI models expand in size (often measured by billions or even trillions of parameters), load balancing for data ingestion has grown in importance for maintaining the reliability, scalability, and cost efficiency of AI factories.
[src:service-mesh-deep/microservices] In software engineering, a **microservice** architecture is an architectural pattern that organizes an application into a collection of loosely coupled, fine-grained services that communicate through lightweight protocols.
[src:service-mesh-deep/microservices] This pattern allows teams to develop, deploy, and scale services independently, improving modularity, scalability, and adaptability.
[src:service-mesh-deep/microservices] However, it introduces additional complexity, particularly in managing distributed systems and inter-service communication, making the initial implementation more challenging compared to a monolithic architecture.
[src:service-mesh-deep/microservices] There is no single, universally agreed-upon definition of microservices.
[src:service-mesh-deep/microservices] However, they are generally characterized by a focus on modularity, with each service designed around a specific business capability.
[src:service-mesh-deep/microservices] These services are loosely coupled, independently deployable, and often developed and scaled separately, enabling greater flexibility and agility in managing complex systems.
[src:service-mesh-deep/microservices] Microservices architecture is closely associated with principles such as domain-driven design, decentralization of data and governance, and the flexibility to use different technologies for individual services to best meet their requirements.
[src:service-mesh-deep/microservices] It is common for microservices architectures to be adopted for cloud-native applications, serverless computing, and applications using lightweight container deployment via OS-level virtualization.
[src:service-mesh-deep/microservices] According to Fowler, because of the large number (when compared to monolithic application implementations) of services, decentralized continuous delivery and DevOps with holistic service monitoring are necessary to effectively develop, maintain, and operate such applications.
[src:service-mesh-deep/microservices] A consequence of (and rationale for) following this approach is that the individual microservices can be individually scaled.
[src:service-mesh-deep/microservices] In the monolithic approach, an application supporting three functions would have to be scaled in its entirety even if only one of these functions had a resource constraint.
[src:service-mesh-deep/microservices] With microservices, only the microservice supporting the function with resource constraints needs to be scaled out, thus providing resource and cost optimization benefits.
[src:service-mesh-deep/microservices] Despite its benefits, microservices architecture introduces challenges such as increased operational complexity, network latency, and the need for robust monitoring and fault tolerance mechanisms.
[src:service-mesh-deep/microservices] Cell-based architecture is a distributed computing design in which computational resources are organized into self-contained units called cells.
[src:service-mesh-deep/microservices] Each cell operates independently, handling a subset of requests while maintaining scalability, fault isolation, and availability.
[src:service-mesh-deep/microservices] A cell typically consists of multiple microservices and functions as an autonomous unit.
[src:service-mesh-deep/microservices] In some implementations, entire sets of microservices are replicated across multiple cells, enabling requests to be rerouted to another operational cell if one experiences a failure.
[src:service-mesh-deep/microservices] This approach is intended to improve system-wide resilience by limiting the impact of localized failures.
[src:service-mesh-deep/microservices] Some implementations incorporate circuit breakers within and between cells.
[src:service-mesh-deep/microservices] Within a cell, circuit breakers may be used to mitigate cascading failures among microservices, while inter-cell circuit breakers can isolate failing cells and redirect traffic to those that remain operational.
[src:service-mesh-deep/microservices] Cell-based architecture has been adopted in certain large-scale distributed systems where fault isolation and redundancy are design priorities.
[src:service-mesh-deep/microservices] Its implementation varies based on system requirements, infrastructure constraints, and specific operational goals.
[src:service-mesh-deep/microservices] In 1999, software developer Peter Rodgers had been working on the Dexter research project at Hewlett Packard Labs, whose aim was to make code less brittle and to make large-scale, complex software systems robust to change.
[src:service-mesh-deep/microservices] Ultimately this path of research led to the development of resource-oriented computing (ROC), a generalized computation abstraction in which REST is a special subset.
[src:service-mesh-deep/microservices] In 2005, during a presentation at the Web Services Edge conference, Rodgers argued for "REST-services" and stated that "Software components are Micro-Web-Services...
[src:service-mesh-deep/microservices] Micro-Services are composed using Unix-like pipelines (the Web meets Unix = true loose-coupling).
[src:service-mesh-deep/microservices] Services can call services (+multiple language run-times).
[src:service-mesh-deep/microservices] Complex service assemblies are abstracted behind simple URI interfaces.
[src:service-mesh-deep/microservices] Also in 2005, Alistair Cockburn wrote about hexagonal architecture which is a software design pattern that is used along with the microservices.
[src:service-mesh-deep/microservices] This pattern makes the design of the microservice possible since it isolates in layers the business logic from the auxiliary services needed in order to deploy and run the microservice completely independent from others.
[src:service-mesh-deep/microservices] Determining the appropriate level of (micro)service granularity in a microservices architecture often requires iterative collaboration between architects and developers.
[src:service-mesh-deep/microservices] This process involves evaluating user requirements, service responsibilities, and architectural characteristics, such as non-functional requirements.
[src:service-mesh-deep/microservices] Neal Ford highlights the role of integrator and disintegrator factors in this context.
[src:service-mesh-deep/microservices] Integrator factors, such as shared transactions or tightly coupled processes, favor combining services, while disintegrator factors, such as fault tolerance or independent scalability, encourage splitting services to meet operational and architectural goals.
[src:service-mesh-deep/microservices] Additionally, fitness functions, as proposed by Neal Ford, can be used to validate architectural decisions and service granularity by continuously measuring system qualities or behaviors that are critical to stakeholders, ensuring alignment with overall architectural objectives.
[src:service-mesh-deep/microservices] In microservices architectures, service granularity influences testing, deployment, performance, and reliability.
[src:service-mesh-deep/microservices] Very fine-grained microservices are typically easier to test and deploy independently, but they often experience lower performance and reduced overall reliability due to increased interservice communication and more complex service choreography.
[src:service-mesh-deep/microservices] Coarse-grained services exhibit contrasting characteristics.
[src:service-mesh-deep/microservices] They generally provide higher robustness and reliability by minimizing communication overhead and coordination complexity, but they are more challenging to test and deploy because modifications affect a broader functional scope.
[src:service-mesh-deep/microservices] The appropriate level of service granularity is determined by business drivers.
[src:service-mesh-deep/microservices] Architectural decisions commonly begin with identifying these drivers and then aligning architectural characteristics such as performance, scalability, reliability, or deployment flexibility to support them.
[src:service-mesh-deep/microservices] A bounded context, a fundamental concept in domain-driven design (DDD), defines a specific area within which a domain model is consistent and valid, ensuring clarity and separation of concerns.
[src:service-mesh-deep/microservices] In microservices architecture, a bounded context often maps to a microservice, but this relationship can vary depending on the design approach.
[src:service-mesh-deep/microservices] A one-to-one relationship, where each bounded context is implemented as a single microservice, is typically ideal as it maintains clear boundaries, reduces coupling, and enables independent deployment and scaling.
[src:service-mesh-deep/microservices] The choice of relationship should balance the principles of DDD with the system's business goals, technical constraints, and operational requirements.
[src:service-mesh-deep/microservices] The architecture introduces additional complexity and new problems to deal with, such as latency, message format design, backup/availability/consistency (BAC), load balancing and fault tolerance.
[src:service-mesh-deep/microservices] All of these problems have to be addressed at scale.
[src:service-mesh-deep/microservices] The complexity of a monolithic application does not disappear if it is re-implemented as a set of microservices.
[src:service-mesh-deep/microservices] Some of the complexity gets translated into operational complexity.
[src:service-mesh-deep/microservices] Other places where the complexity manifests itself are increased network traffic and slower performance.
[src:service-mesh-deep/microservices] Also, an application made up of any number of microservices has a larger number of interface points to access its respective ecosystem, which increases the architectural complexity.
[src:service-mesh-deep/microservices] Various organizing principles (such as hypermedia as the engine of application state (HATEOAS), interface and data model documentation captured via Swagger, etc.) have been applied to reduce the impact of such additional complexity.
[src:service-mesh-deep/microservices] Microservices are susceptible to the fallacies of distributed computing – a series of misconceptions that can lead to significant issues in software development and deployment.
[src:service-mesh-deep/microservices] Ideally, microservices follow a "share-nothing" architecture.
[src:service-mesh-deep/microservices] However, in practice, microservices architectures often encounter situations where code must be shared across services.
[src:service-mesh-deep/microservices] Each approach has its advantages and trade-offs, depending on the specific context and requirements.
[src:service-mesh-deep/microservices] Richards & Ford in *Fundamentals of software architecture* (2020) propose each microservice should have its own architectural characteristics (a.k.a. non functional requirements), and architects should not define uniform characteristics for the entire distributed system.
[src:service-mesh-deep/microservices] To avoid having to coordinate deployments across different microservices, Sam Newman suggests keeping the interfaces of microservices stable and making backwards-compatible changes as interfaces evolve.
[src:service-mesh-deep/microservices] On the topic of testing, Newman in *Building Microservices* (2015) proposes consumer-driven contract testing as a better alternative to traditional end-to-end testing in the context of microservices.
[src:service-mesh-deep/microservices] He also suggests the use of log aggregation and metrics aggregation as well as distributed tracing tools to ensure the observability of systems composed of microservices.
[src:service-mesh-deep/microservices] Computer microservices can be implemented in different programming languages and might use different infrastructures.
[src:service-mesh-deep/microservices] Therefore, the most important technology choices are the way microservices communicate with each other (synchronous, asynchronous, UI integration) and the protocols used for the communication (e.g.
[src:service-mesh-deep/microservices] In a traditional system, most technology choices like the programming language impact the whole system.
[src:service-mesh-deep/microservices] Therefore, the approach to choosing technologies is quite different.
[src:service-mesh-deep/microservices] The Eclipse Foundation has published a specification for developing microservices, Eclipse MicroProfile.
[src:service-mesh-deep/microservices] In a service mesh, each service instance is paired with an instance of a reverse proxy server, called a service proxy, sidecar proxy, or sidecar.
[src:service-mesh-deep/microservices] The service instance and sidecar proxy share a container, and the containers are managed by a container orchestration tool such as Kubernetes, Docker Swarm, or DC/OS.
[src:service-mesh-deep/microservices] The service proxies are responsible for communication with other service instances and can support capabilities such as service (instance) discovery, load balancing, authentication and authorization, secure communications, and others.
[src:service-mesh-deep/mutual-authentication] Mutual authentication is a desired characteristic in verification schemes that transmit sensitive data, in order to ensure data security.
[src:service-mesh-deep/mutual-authentication] Mutual authentication can be accomplished with two types of credentials: usernames and passwords, and public key certificates.
[src:service-mesh-deep/mutual-authentication] Mutual authentication is often employed in the Internet of Things (IoT).
[src:service-mesh-deep/mutual-authentication] Writing effective security schemes in IoT systems is challenging, especially when schemes are desired to be lightweight and have low computational costs.
[src:service-mesh-deep/mutual-authentication] Mutual authentication is a crucial security step that can defend against many adversarial attacks, which otherwise can have large consequences if IoT systems (such as e-Healthcare servers) are hacked.
[src:service-mesh-deep/mutual-authentication] In scheme analyses done of past works, a lack of mutual authentication had been considered a weakness in data transmission schemes.
[src:service-mesh-deep/mutual-authentication] Schemes that have a mutual authentication step may use different methods of encryption, communication, and verification, but they all share one thing in common: each entity involved in the communication is verified.
[src:service-mesh-deep/mutual-authentication] If Alice wants to communicate with Bob, they will both authenticate the other and verify that it is who they are expecting to communicate with before any data or messages are transmitted.
[src:service-mesh-deep/mutual-authentication] The message is then decrypted with Bob's secret key, giving Alice's ID.
[src:service-mesh-deep/mutual-authentication] Bob sends Alice a message back, encrypted with Alice's public key, to show that Bob is a valid user.
[src:service-mesh-deep/mutual-authentication] The message is then decrypted with Alice's secret key, giving Bob's ID.
[src:service-mesh-deep/mutual-authentication] At this point, both parties are verified to be who they claim to be and safe for the other to communicate with.
[src:service-mesh-deep/mutual-authentication] Lastly, Alice and Bob will create a shared secret key so that they can continue communicating in a secure manner.
[src:service-mesh-deep/mutual-authentication] To verify that mutual authentication has occurred successfully, Burrows-Abadi-Needham logic (BAN logic) is a well regarded and widely accepted method to use, because it verifies that a message came from a trustworthy entity.
[src:service-mesh-deep/mutual-authentication] BAN logic first assumes an entity is not to be trusted, and then will verify its legality.
[src:service-mesh-deep/mutual-authentication] or intercept a message, and sometimes alter the intended message for the recipient.
[src:service-mesh-deep/mutual-authentication] The two parties openly receive messages without verifying the sender, so they do not realize an adversary has inserted themselves into the communication line.
[src:service-mesh-deep/mutual-authentication] Mutual authentication can prevent MITM attacks because both the sender and recipient verify each other before sending them their message keys, so if one of the parties is not verified to be who they claim they are, the session will end.
[src:service-mesh-deep/mutual-authentication] A replay attack is similar to a MITM attack in which older messages are replayed out of context to fool the server.
[src:service-mesh-deep/mutual-authentication] because timestamps are a verification factor that are used in the protocols.
[src:service-mesh-deep/mutual-authentication] If the change in time is greater than the maximum allowed time delay, the session will be aborted.
[src:service-mesh-deep/mutual-authentication] Similarly, messages can include a randomly generated number to keep track of when a message was sent.
[src:service-mesh-deep/mutual-authentication] before allowing any further communication and access.
[src:service-mesh-deep/mutual-authentication] Impersonation attacks refer to malicious attacks where a user or individual pretends to be an authorized user to gain unauthorized access to a system while feigning permission.
[src:service-mesh-deep/mutual-authentication] When each party authenticates the other, they send each other a certificate that only the other party knows how to unscramble, verifying themselves as a trusted source.
[src:service-mesh-deep/mutual-authentication] In this way, adversaries cannot use impersonation attacks because they do not have the correct certificate to act as if they are the other party.
[src:service-mesh-deep/mutual-authentication] Mutual authentication also ensures information integrity because if the parties are verified to be the correct source, then the information received is reliable as well.
[src:service-mesh-deep/mutual-authentication] By default the TLS protocol only proves the identity of the server to the client using X.509 certificates, and the authentication of the client to the server is left to the application layer.
[src:service-mesh-deep/mutual-authentication] TLS also offers client-to-server authentication using client-side X.509 authentication.
[src:service-mesh-deep/mutual-authentication] As it requires provisioning of the certificates to the clients and involves a less user-friendly experience, it is rarely used in end-user applications.
[src:service-mesh-deep/mutual-authentication] mTLS is also used in microservices-based applications based on runtimes such as Dapr, via systems like SPIFFE.
[src:service-mesh-deep/mutual-authentication] While lightweight schemes and secure schemes are not mutually exclusive, adding a mutual authentication step to data transmissions protocols can often increase performance runtime and computational costs.
[src:service-mesh-deep/mutual-authentication] This can become an issue for network systems that cannot handle large amounts of data or those that constantly have to update for new real-time data (e.g. location tracking, real-time health data).
[src:service-mesh-deep/mutual-authentication] Thus, it becomes a desired characteristic of many mutual authentication schemes to have lightweight properties (e.g. have a low memory footprint) in order to accommodate the system that is storing a lot of data.
[src:service-mesh-deep/mutual-authentication] Many systems implement cloud computing, which allows quick access to large amounts of data, but sometimes large amounts of data can slow down communication.
[src:service-mesh-deep/mutual-authentication] Even with edge-based cloud computing, which is faster than general cloud computing due to a closer proximity between the server and user, lightweight schemes allow for more speed when managing larger amounts of data.
[src:service-mesh-deep/mutual-authentication] One solution to keep schemes lightweight during the mutual authentication process is to limit the number of bits used during communication.
[src:service-mesh-deep/mutual-authentication] Applications that solely rely on device-to-device (D2D) communication, where multiple devices can communicate locally in close proximities, removes the third party network.
[src:service-mesh-deep/mutual-authentication] This in turn can speed up communication time.
[src:service-mesh-deep/mutual-authentication] However, the authentication still occurs through insecure channels, so researchers believe it is still important to ensure mutual authentication occurs in order to keep a secure scheme.
[src:service-mesh-deep/mutual-authentication] Schemes may sacrifice a better runtime or storage cost when ensuring mutual authentication in order to prioritize protecting the sensitive data.
[src:service-mesh-deep/mutual-authentication] In mutual authentication schemes that require a user's input password as part of the verification process, there is a higher vulnerability to hackers because the password is human-made rather than a computer-generated certificate.
[src:service-mesh-deep/mutual-authentication] While applications could simply require users to use a computer-generated password, it is inconvenient for people to remember.
[src:service-mesh-deep/mutual-authentication] User-made passwords and the ability to change one's password are important for making an application user-friendly, so many schemes work to accommodate the characteristic.
[src:service-mesh-deep/mutual-authentication] Researchers note that a password based protocol with mutual authentication is important because user identities and passwords are still protected, as the messages are only readable to the two parties involved.
[src:service-mesh-deep/mutual-authentication] However, a negative aspect about password-based authentication is that password tables can take up a lot of memory space.
[src:service-mesh-deep/mutual-authentication] One way around using a lot of memory during a password-based authentication scheme is to implement one-time passwords (OTP), which is a password sent to the user via SMS or email.
[src:service-mesh-deep/mutual-authentication] OTPs are time-sensitive, which means that they will expire after a certain amount of time and that memory does not need to be stored.
[src:service-mesh-deep/mutual-authentication] Recently, more schemes have higher level authentication than password based schemes.
[src:service-mesh-deep/mutual-authentication] While password-based authentication is considered as "single-factor authentication," schemes are beginning to implement smart card (two-factor) or biometric-based (three-factor) authentication schemes.
[src:service-mesh-deep/mutual-authentication] Smart cards are simpler to implement and easy for authentication, but still have risks of being tampered with.
[src:service-mesh-deep/mutual-authentication] Biometrics have grown more popular over password-based schemes because it is more difficult to copy or guess session keys when using biometrics, but it can be difficult to encrypt noisy data.
[src:service-mesh-deep/mutual-authentication] Due to these security risks and limitations, schemes can still employ mutual authentication regardless of how many authentication factors are added.
[src:service-mesh-deep/mutual-authentication] Mutual authentication is often found in schemes employed in the Internet of Things (IoT), where physical objects are incorporated into the Internet and can communicate via IP address.
[src:service-mesh-deep/mutual-authentication] Authentication schemes can be applied to many types of systems that involve data transmission.
[src:service-mesh-deep/mutual-authentication] As the Internet's presence in mechanical systems increases, writing effective security schemes for large numbers of users, objects, and servers can become challenging, especially when needing schemes to be lightweight and have low computational costs.
[src:service-mesh-deep/mutual-authentication] Instead of password-based authentication, devices will use certificates to verify each other's identities.
[src:service-mesh-deep/mutual-authentication] Mutual authentication can be satisfied in radio network schemes, where data transmissions through radio frequencies are secure after verifying the sender and receiver.
[src:service-mesh-deep/mutual-authentication] Radio frequency identification (RFID) tags are commonly used for object detection, which many manufacturers are implementing into their warehouse systems for automation.
[src:service-mesh-deep/mutual-authentication] This allows for a faster way to keep up with inventory and track objects.
[src:service-mesh-deep/mutual-authentication] However, keeping track of items in a system with RFID tags that transmit data to a cloud server increases the chances of security risks, as there are now more digital elements to keep track of.
[src:service-mesh-deep/mutual-authentication] A three way mutual authentication can occur between RFID tags, the tag readers, and the cloud network that stores this data in order to keep RFID tag data secure and unable to be manipulated.
[src:service-mesh-deep/mutual-authentication] Similarly, an alternate RFID tag and reader system that assigns designated readers to tags has been proposed for extra security and low memory cost.
[src:service-mesh-deep/mutual-authentication] Instead of considering all tag readers as one entity, only certain readers can read specific tags.
[src:service-mesh-deep/mutual-authentication] With this method, if a reader is breached, it will not affect the whole system.
[src:service-mesh-deep/mutual-authentication] Individual readers will communicate with specific tags during mutual authentication, which runs in constant time as readers use the same private key for the authentication process.
[src:service-mesh-deep/mutual-authentication] Many e-Healthcare systems that remotely monitor patient health data use wireless body area networks (WBAN) that transmit data through radio frequencies.
[src:service-mesh-deep/mutual-authentication] This is beneficial for patients that should not be disturbed while being monitored, and can reduced the workload for medical worker and allow them to focus on the more hands-on jobs.
[src:service-mesh-deep/mutual-authentication] e-Healthcare clouds are another way to store patient data collected remotely.
[src:service-mesh-deep/mutual-authentication] Clouds are useful for storing large amounts of data, such as medical information, that can be accessed by many devices whenever needed.
[src:service-mesh-deep/mutual-authentication] Telecare Medical Information Systems (TMIS), an important way for medical patients to receive healthcare remotely, can ensure secured data with mutual authentication verification schemes.
[src:service-mesh-deep/mutual-authentication] Blockchain is one way that has been proposed to mutually authenticate the user to the database, by authenticating with the main mediBchain node and keeping patient anonymity.
[src:service-mesh-deep/mutual-authentication] Fog-cloud computing is a networking system that can handle large amounts of data, but still has limitations regarding computational and memory cost.
[src:service-mesh-deep/mutual-authentication] Mobile edge computing (MEC) is considered to be an improved, more lightweight fog-cloud computing networking system, and can be used for medical technology that also revolves around location-based data.
[src:service-mesh-deep/mutual-authentication] Due to the large physical range required of locational tracking, 5G networks can send data to the edge of the cloud to store data.
[src:service-mesh-deep/mutual-authentication] An application like smart watches that track patient health data can be used to call the nearest hospital if the patient shows a negative change in vitals.
[src:service-mesh-deep/mutual-authentication] Fog node networks can be implemented in car automation, keeping data about the car and its surrounding states secure.
[src:service-mesh-deep/mutual-authentication] By authenticating the fog nodes and the vehicle, vehicular handoff becomes a safe process and the car’s system is safe from hackers.
[src:service-mesh-deep/mutual-authentication] Many systems that do not require a human user as part of the system also have protocols that mutually authenticate between parties.
[src:service-mesh-deep/mutual-authentication] In unmanned aerial vehicle (UAV) systems, a platform authentication occurs rather than user authentication.
[src:service-mesh-deep/mutual-authentication] Mutual authentication during vehicle communication prevents one vehicle's system from being breached, which can then affect the whole system negatively.
[src:service-mesh-deep/mutual-authentication] For example, a system of drones can be employed for agriculture work and cargo delivery, but if one drone were to be breached, the whole system has the potential to collapse.
[src:service-mesh-deep/proxy-server] In computer networking, a **proxy server** is a intermediary server application between a client requesting a resource and the server then providing that resource.
[src:service-mesh-deep/proxy-server] Instead of connecting directly to a server that can fulfil a request for a resource, such as a file or web page, the client directs the request to the proxy server, which evaluates the request and performs the required network transactions.
[src:service-mesh-deep/proxy-server] This serves as a method to control the complexity of the request or provide additional benefits such as load balancing, privacy or security.
[src:service-mesh-deep/proxy-server] Proxies were devised to add structure and encapsulation to distributed systems.
[src:service-mesh-deep/proxy-server] A proxy server may reside on the user's **local computer**, or at any point between the user's computer and the destination servers.
[src:service-mesh-deep/proxy-server] A proxy server that passes unmodified requests and responses is usually called a gateway or sometimes a *tunneling proxy*.
[src:service-mesh-deep/proxy-server] A forward proxy is an Internet-facing proxy used to retrieve data from a wide range of sources (in most cases, anywhere on the Internet).
[src:service-mesh-deep/proxy-server] A reverse proxy is usually an internal-facing proxy used as a front-end to control and protect access to a server on a private network.
[src:service-mesh-deep/proxy-server] A reverse proxy commonly also performs tasks such as load-balancing, authentication, decryption, and caching.
[src:service-mesh-deep/proxy-server] An open proxy is a forwarding proxy server that is accessible by any Internet user.
[src:service-mesh-deep/proxy-server] In 2008, network security expert Gordon Lyon estimated that "hundreds of thousands" of open proxies are operated on the Internet.
[src:service-mesh-deep/proxy-server] A reverse proxy (or surrogate) is a proxy server that appears to clients to be an ordinary server.
[src:service-mesh-deep/proxy-server] Reverse proxies send requests to one or more ordinary servers that handle the request.
[src:service-mesh-deep/proxy-server] The response from the original server is returned as if it came directly from the proxy server, leaving the client with no knowledge of the original server.
[src:service-mesh-deep/proxy-server] Reverse proxies are installed in the vicinity of one or more web servers.
[src:service-mesh-deep/proxy-server] All traffic coming from the Internet and with a destination of one of the neighborhood's web servers goes through the proxy server.
[src:service-mesh-deep/proxy-server] The use of "reverse" originates in its counterpart, the "forward" proxy.
[src:service-mesh-deep/proxy-server] The reverse proxy sits closer to the web server and serves only a restricted set of websites.
[src:service-mesh-deep/proxy-server] A forward proxy is a server that routes traffic between clients and another system, which is, in most cases, external to the network.
[src:service-mesh-deep/proxy-server] This means it can regulate traffic according to preset policies, convert and mask client IP addresses, enforce security protocols, and block unknown traffic.
[src:service-mesh-deep/proxy-server] A forward proxy enhances security and policy enforcement within an internal network.
[src:service-mesh-deep/proxy-server] A reverse proxy, instead of protecting the client, is used to protect the servers.
[src:service-mesh-deep/proxy-server] A reverse proxy accepts a request from a client, forwards that request to another one of many other servers, and then returns the results from the server that specifically processed the request to the client.
[src:service-mesh-deep/proxy-server] Effectively, a reverse proxy acts as a gateway between clients, users, and application servers and handles all the traffic routing whilst also protecting the identity of the server that physically processes the request.
[src:service-mesh-deep/proxy-server] A content-filtering web proxy server provides administrative control over the content that may be relayed in one or both directions through the proxy.
[src:service-mesh-deep/proxy-server] It is commonly used in both commercial and non-commercial organizations (especially schools) to ensure that Internet usage conforms to acceptable use policy.
[src:service-mesh-deep/proxy-server] Content filtering proxy servers will often support user authentication to control web access.
[src:service-mesh-deep/proxy-server] It also usually produces logs, either to give detailed information about the URLs accessed by specific users or to monitor bandwidth usage statistics.
[src:service-mesh-deep/proxy-server] It may also communicate to daemon-based or ICAP-based antivirus software to provide security against viruses and other malware by scanning incoming content in real-time before it enters the network.
[src:service-mesh-deep/proxy-server] Many workplaces, schools, and colleges restrict websites and online services that are accessible and available in their buildings.
[src:service-mesh-deep/proxy-server] Governments also censor undesirable content.
[src:service-mesh-deep/proxy-server] This is done either with a specialized proxy, called a content filter (both commercial and free products are available), or by using a cache-extension protocol such as ICAP, which allows plug-in extensions to an open caching architecture.
[src:service-mesh-deep/proxy-server] Websites commonly used by students to circumvent filters and access blocked content often include a proxy, from which the user can then access the websites that the filter is trying to block.
[src:service-mesh-deep/proxy-server] Requests may be filtered by several methods, such as a URL or DNS blacklists, URL regex filtering, MIME filtering, or content keyword filtering.
[src:service-mesh-deep/proxy-server] Blacklists are often provided and maintained by web-filtering companies, often grouped into categories (pornography, gambling, shopping, social networks, etc.).
[src:service-mesh-deep/proxy-server] The proxy then fetches the content, assuming the requested URL is acceptable.
[src:service-mesh-deep/proxy-server] At this point, a dynamic filter may be applied on the return path.
[src:service-mesh-deep/proxy-server] For example, JPEG files could be blocked based on fleshtone matches, or language filters could dynamically detect unwanted language.
[src:service-mesh-deep/proxy-server] If the content is rejected, then an HTTP fetch error may be returned to the requester.
[src:service-mesh-deep/proxy-server] Most web filtering companies use an internet-wide crawling robot that assesses the likelihood that content is a certain type.
[src:service-mesh-deep/proxy-server] Manual labor is used to correct the resultant database based on complaints or known flaws in the content-matching algorithms.
[src:service-mesh-deep/proxy-server] Some proxies scan outbound content, e.g., for data loss prevention, or scan content for malicious software.
[src:service-mesh-deep/proxy-server] Web filtering proxies are not able to peer inside secure sockets HTTP transactions, assuming the chain-of-trust of SSL/TLS (Transport Layer Security) has not been tampered with.
[src:service-mesh-deep/proxy-server] The SSL/TLS chain-of-trust relies on trusted root certificate authorities.
[src:service-mesh-deep/proxy-server] In a workplace setting where the client is managed by the organization, devices may be configured to trust a root certificate whose private key is known to the proxy.
[src:service-mesh-deep/proxy-server] In such situations, proxy analysis of the contents of an SSL/TLS transaction becomes possible.
[src:service-mesh-deep/proxy-server] The proxy is effectively operating a man-in-the-middle attack, allowed by the client's trust of a root certificate that the proxy owns.
[src:service-mesh-deep/proxy-server] If the destination server filters content based on the origin of the request, the use of a proxy can circumvent this filter.
[src:service-mesh-deep/proxy-server] For example, a server using IP-based geolocation to restrict its service to a certain country can be accessed using a proxy located in that country to access the service.
[src:service-mesh-deep/proxy-server] Web proxies are the most common means of bypassing government censorship, although no more than 3% of Internet users use any circumvention tools.
[src:service-mesh-deep/proxy-server] Some proxy service providers allow businesses access to their proxy network for rerouting traffic for business intelligence purposes.
[src:service-mesh-deep/proxy-server] In some cases, users can circumvent proxies that filter using blacklists by using services designed to proxy information from a non-blacklisted location.
[src:service-mesh-deep/proxy-server] Proxies can be installed to eavesdrop upon the data-flow between client machines and the web.
[src:service-mesh-deep/proxy-server] All content sent or accessed, including passwords submitted and cookies used, can be captured and analyzed by the proxy operator.
[src:service-mesh-deep/proxy-server] For this reason, passwords to online services (such as webmail and banking) should always be exchanged over a cryptographically secured connection, such as SSL.
[src:service-mesh-deep/proxy-server] By chaining the proxies that do not reveal data about the original requester, it is possible to obfuscate activities from the eyes of the user's destination.
[src:service-mesh-deep/proxy-server] However, more traces will be left on the intermediate hops, which could be used or offered up to trace the user's activities.
[src:service-mesh-deep/proxy-server] If the policies and administrators of these other proxies are unknown, the user may fall victim to a false sense of security just because those details are out of sight and mind.
[src:service-mesh-deep/proxy-server] In what is more of an inconvenience than a risk, proxy users may find themselves being blocked from certain websites, as numerous forums and websites block IP addresses from proxies known to have spammed or trolled the site.
[src:service-mesh-deep/proxy-server] Proxy bouncing can be used to maintain privacy.
[src:service-mesh-deep/proxy-server] A **caching proxy** server accelerates service requests by retrieving the content saved from a previous request made by the same client or even other clients.
[src:service-mesh-deep/proxy-server] Caching proxies keep local copies of frequently requested resources, allowing large organizations to significantly reduce their upstream bandwidth usage and costs, while significantly increasing performance.
[src:service-mesh-deep/proxy-server] Most ISPs and large businesses have a caching proxy.
[src:service-mesh-deep/proxy-server] Caching proxies were the first kind of proxy server.
[src:service-mesh-deep/proxy-server] Web proxies are commonly used to cache web pages from a web server.
[src:service-mesh-deep/proxy-server] Poorly implemented caching proxies can cause problems, such as an inability to use user authentication.
[src:service-mesh-deep/proxy-server] A proxy that is designed to mitigate specific link-related issues or degradation is a Performance Enhancing Proxy (PEPs).
[src:service-mesh-deep/proxy-server] These are typically used to improve TCP performance in the presence of high round-trip times or high packet loss (such as wireless or mobile phone networks); or highly asymmetric links featuring very different upload and download rates.
[src:service-mesh-deep/proxy-server] PEPs can make more efficient use of the network, for example, by merging TCP ACKs (acknowledgements) or compressing data sent at the application layer.
[src:service-mesh-deep/proxy-server] A translation proxy is a proxy server that is used to localize a website experience for different markets.
[src:service-mesh-deep/proxy-server] Traffic from the global audience is routed through the translation proxy to the source website.
[src:service-mesh-deep/proxy-server] As visitors browse the proxied site, requests go back to the source site where pages are rendered.
[src:service-mesh-deep/proxy-server] The original language content in the response is replaced by the translated content as it passes back through the proxy.
[src:service-mesh-deep/proxy-server] The translations used in a translation proxy can be either machine translation, human translation, or a combination of machine and human translation.
[src:service-mesh-deep/proxy-server] Different translation proxy implementations have different capabilities.
[src:service-mesh-deep/proxy-server] Some allow further customization of the source site for the local audiences, such as excluding the source content or substituting the source content with the original local content.
[src:service-mesh-deep/proxy-server] An anonymous proxy server (sometimes called a web proxy) generally attempts to anonymize web surfing.
[src:service-mesh-deep/proxy-server] Anonymizers may be differentiated into several varieties.
[src:service-mesh-deep/proxy-server] The destination server (the server that ultimately satisfies the web request) receives requests from the anonymizing proxy server and thus does not receive information about the end user's address.
[src:service-mesh-deep/proxy-server] The requests are not anonymous to the anonymizing proxy server, however, and so a degree of trust is present between the proxy server and the user.
[src:service-mesh-deep/proxy-server] Many proxy servers are funded through a continuous advertising link to the user.
[src:service-mesh-deep/proxy-server] Advertisers use proxy servers for validating, checking, and quality assuring geotargeted ads.
[src:service-mesh-deep/proxy-server] A geotargeting ad server checks the request source IP address and uses a geo-IP database to determine the geographic source of requests.
[src:service-mesh-deep/proxy-server] Using a proxy server that is physically located inside a specific country or a city gives advertisers the ability to test geotargeted ads.
[src:service-mesh-deep/proxy-server] A proxy can keep the internal network structure of a company secret by using network address translation, which can help the security of the internal network.
[src:service-mesh-deep/proxy-server] This makes requests from machines and users on the local network anonymous.
[src:service-mesh-deep/proxy-server] Proxies can also be combined with firewalls.
[src:service-mesh-deep/proxy-server] An incorrectly configured proxy can provide access to a network otherwise isolated from the Internet.
[src:service-mesh-deep/proxy-server] Proxies allow websites to make web requests to externally hosted resources (e.g., images, music files, etc.) when cross-domain restrictions prohibit the website from linking directly to the outside domains.
[src:service-mesh-deep/proxy-server] Proxies also allow the browser to make web requests to externally hosted content on behalf of a website when cross-domain restrictions (in place to protect websites from the likes of data theft) prohibit the browser from directly accessing the outside domains.
[src:service-mesh-deep/proxy-server] Secondary market brokers use web proxy servers to circumvent restrictions on online purchases of limited products such as limited sneakers or tickets.
[src:service-mesh-deep/proxy-server] The request from the client is the same as a regular HTTP request except the full URL is passed, instead of just the path.
[src:service-mesh-deep/proxy-server] This request is sent to the proxy server, the proxy makes the request specified, and returns the response.
[src:service-mesh-deep/proxy-server] Some web proxies allow the HTTP CONNECT method to set up forwarding of arbitrary data through the connection; a common policy is to only forward port 443 to allow HTTPS traffic.
[src:service-mesh-deep/proxy-server] Examples of web proxy servers include Apache (with mod_proxy or Traffic Server), HAProxy, IIS configured as proxy (e.g., with Application Request Routing), Nginx, Privoxy, Squid, Varnish (reverse proxy only), WinGate, Ziproxy, Tinyproxy, RabbIT and Polipo.
[src:service-mesh-deep/proxy-server] For clients, the problem of complex or multiple proxy-servers is solved by a client-server Proxy auto-config protocol (*PAC file*).
[src:service-mesh-deep/proxy-server] Various operating systems (such as Windows, Android, macOS, iOS, Xbox OS and PlayStation OS) and various browsers (such as Edge, Chrome, Safari and Firefox) can support Web proxy.
[src:service-mesh-deep/proxy-server] SOCKS also forwards arbitrary data after a connection phase, and is similar to HTTP CONNECT in web proxies.
[src:service-mesh-deep/proxy-server] An **intercepting proxy** redirects or filters client traffic without being explicitly selected by the client.
[src:service-mesh-deep/proxy-server] It is therefore often deployed without requiring browser or application proxy settings, and clients may be unaware that their traffic is passing through a proxy.
[src:service-mesh-deep/proxy-server] In HTTP terminology, an interception proxy differs from a conventional HTTP proxy because it is not chosen by the user agent; instead, it is placed in the network path and filters or redirects outgoing traffic, commonly TCP port 80 traffic.
[src:service-mesh-deep/proxy-server] TCP Intercept is a traffic filtering security feature that protects TCP servers from TCP SYN flood attacks, which are a type of denial-of-service attack.
[src:service-mesh-deep/proxy-server] TCP Intercept is available for IP traffic only.
[src:service-mesh-deep/proxy-server] In 2009 a security flaw in the way that transparent proxies operate was published by Robert Auger, and the Computer Emergency Response Team issued an advisory listing dozens of affected transparent and intercepting proxy servers.
[src:service-mesh-deep/proxy-server] Intercepting proxies are commonly used in businesses to enforce acceptable use policies and to ease administrative overheads since no client browser configuration is required.
[src:service-mesh-deep/proxy-server] This second reason, however, is mitigated by features such as Active Directory group policy, or DHCP and automatic proxy detection.
[src:service-mesh-deep/proxy-server] Intercepting proxies are also commonly used by ISPs in some countries to save upstream bandwidth and improve customer response times by caching.
[src:service-mesh-deep/proxy-server] This is more common in countries where bandwidth is more limited (e.g, island nations) or must be paid for.
[src:service-mesh-deep/proxy-server] The diversion or interception of a TCP connection creates several issues.
[src:service-mesh-deep/proxy-server] First, the original destination IP and port must somehow be communicated to the proxy.
[src:service-mesh-deep/proxy-server] This is not always possible (e.g., where the gateway and proxy reside on different hosts).
[src:service-mesh-deep/proxy-server] There is a class of cross-site attacks that depend on certain behaviors of intercepting proxies that do not check or have access to information about the original (intercepted) destination.
[src:service-mesh-deep/proxy-server] This problem may be resolved by using an integrated packet-level and application-level appliance or software, which is then able to communicate this information between the packet handler and the proxy.
[src:service-mesh-deep/proxy-server] Intercepting also creates problems for HTTP authentication, especially connection-oriented authentication such as NTLM, as the client browser believes it is talking to a server rather than a proxy.
[src:service-mesh-deep/proxy-server] This can cause problems where an intercepting proxy requires authentication, and then the user connects to a site that also requires authentication.
[src:service-mesh-deep/proxy-server] Finally, intercepting connections can cause problems for HTTP caches, as some requests and responses become uncacheable by a shared cache.
[src:service-mesh-deep/proxy-server] In integrated firewall/proxy servers where the router/firewall is on the same host as the proxy, communicating original destination information can be done by any method, for example, Microsoft TMG or WinGate.
[src:service-mesh-deep/proxy-server] Interception can also be performed using Cisco's WCCP (Web Cache Control Protocol).
[src:service-mesh-deep/proxy-server] This proprietary protocol resides on the router and is configured from the cache, allowing the cache to determine what ports and traffic are sent to it via transparent redirection from the router.
[src:service-mesh-deep/proxy-server] This redirection can occur in one of two ways: GRE tunneling (OSI Layer 3) or MAC rewrites (OSI Layer 2).
[src:service-mesh-deep/proxy-server] Once traffic reaches the proxy machine itself, interception is commonly performed with NAT (Network Address Translation).
[src:service-mesh-deep/proxy-server] Such setups are invisible to the client browser, but leave the proxy visible to the web server and other devices on the internet side of the proxy.
[src:service-mesh-deep/proxy-server] Recent Linux and some BSD releases provide TPROXY (transparent proxy), which performs IP-level (OSI Layer 3) transparent interception and spoofing of outbound traffic, hiding the proxy IP address from other network devices.
[src:service-mesh-deep/proxy-server] A CGI web proxy accepts target URLs using a Web form in the user's browser window, processes the request, and returns the results to the user's browser.
[src:service-mesh-deep/proxy-server] Consequently, it can be used on a device or network that does not allow "true" proxy settings to be changed.
[src:service-mesh-deep/proxy-server] The first recorded CGI proxy, named "rover" at the time but renamed in 1998 to "CGIProxy", was developed by American computer scientist James Marshall in early 1996 for an article in "Unix Review" by Rich Morin.
[src:service-mesh-deep/proxy-server] The majority of CGI proxies are powered by one of CGIProxy (written in the Perl language), Glype (written in the PHP language), or PHProxy (written in the PHP language).
[src:service-mesh-deep/proxy-server] As of April 2016, CGIProxy has received about two million downloads, Glype has received more than half a million downloads, whilst PHProxy still receives hundreds of downloads per week.
[src:service-mesh-deep/proxy-server] Despite waning in popularity due to VPNs and other privacy methods, as of September 2021 there are still a few hundred CGI proxies online.
[src:service-mesh-deep/proxy-server] Some CGI proxies were set up for purposes such as making websites more accessible to disabled people, but have since been shut down due to excessive traffic, usually caused by a third party advertising the service as a means to bypass local filtering.
[src:service-mesh-deep/proxy-server] Since many of these users do not care about the collateral damage they are causing, it became necessary for organizations to hide their proxies, disclosing the URLs only to those who take the trouble to contact the organization and demonstrate a genuine need.
[src:service-mesh-deep/proxy-server] A suffix proxy allows a user to access web content by appending the name of the proxy server to the URL of the requested content (e.g., "en.wikipedia.org.*SuffixProxy.com*").
[src:service-mesh-deep/proxy-server] Suffix proxy servers are easier to use than regular proxy servers, but they do not offer high levels of anonymity, and their primary use is for bypassing web filters.
[src:service-mesh-deep/proxy-server] However, this is rarely used due to more advanced web filters.
[src:service-mesh-deep/proxy-server] Tor is a system intended to provide online anonymity.
[src:service-mesh-deep/proxy-server] Tor client software routes Internet traffic through a worldwide volunteer network of servers for concealing a user's computer location or usage from someone conducting network surveillance or traffic analysis.
[src:service-mesh-deep/proxy-server] Using Tor makes tracing Internet activity more difficult, and is intended to protect users' personal freedom and their online privacy.
[src:service-mesh-deep/proxy-server] This reduces the possibility of the original data being unscrambled or understood in transit.
[src:service-mesh-deep/proxy-server] The I2P anonymous network ('I2P') is a proxy network aiming at online anonymity.
[src:service-mesh-deep/proxy-server] It implements garlic routing, which is an enhancement of Tor's onion routing.
[src:service-mesh-deep/proxy-server] I2P is fully distributed and works by encrypting all communications in various layers and relaying them through a network of routers run by volunteers in various locations.
[src:service-mesh-deep/proxy-server] By keeping the source of the information hidden, I2P offers censorship resistance.
[src:service-mesh-deep/proxy-server] The goals of I2P are to protect users' personal freedom, privacy, and ability to conduct confidential business.
[src:service-mesh-deep/proxy-server] Each user of I2P runs an I2P router on their computer (node).
[src:service-mesh-deep/proxy-server] The I2P router takes care of finding other peers and building anonymizing tunnels through them.
[src:service-mesh-deep/proxy-server] I2P provides proxies for all protocols (HTTP, IRC, SOCKS, ...).
[src:service-mesh-deep/proxy-server] The proxy concept refers to a layer-7 application in the OSI reference model.
[src:service-mesh-deep/proxy-server] Network address translation (NAT) is similar to a proxy but operates in layer 3.
[src:service-mesh-deep/proxy-server] In the client configuration of layer-3 NAT, configuring the gateway is sufficient.
[src:service-mesh-deep/proxy-server] However, for the client configuration of a layer-7 proxy, the destination of the packets that the client generates must always be the proxy server (layer 7), then the proxy server reads each packet and finds out the true destination.
[src:service-mesh-deep/proxy-server] Because NAT operates at layer 3, it is less resource-intensive than the layer-7 proxy, but also less flexible.
[src:service-mesh-deep/proxy-server] As we compare these two technologies, we might encounter a terminology known as 'transparent firewall'.
[src:service-mesh-deep/proxy-server] **Transparent firewall** means that the proxy uses the layer-7 proxy advantages without the knowledge of the client.
[src:service-mesh-deep/proxy-server] The client presumes that the gateway is a NAT in layer 3, and it does not have any idea about the inside of the packet, but through this method, the layer-3 packets are sent to the layer-7 proxy for investigation.
[src:service-mesh-deep/proxy-server] A DNS proxy server takes DNS queries from a (usually local) network and forwards them to an Internet Domain Name Server.
[src:service-mesh-deep/proxy-server] Some client programs "SOCKS-ify" requests, which allows adaptation of any networked software to connect to external networks via certain types of proxy servers (mostly SOCKS).
[src:service-mesh-deep/proxy-server] A residential proxy (RESIP) is an intermediary that uses a real IP address provided by an Internet service provider with physical devices such as mobile phones and end-user computers.
[src:service-mesh-deep/proxy-server] Instead of connecting directly to a server, residential proxy users connect to the target through residential IP addresses.
[src:service-mesh-deep/proxy-server] The target then identifies them as organic internet users.
[src:service-mesh-deep/proxy-server] It does not let any tracking tool identify the reallocation of the user.
[src:service-mesh-deep/proxy-server] Any residential proxy can send any number of concurrent requests, and IP addresses are directly related to a specific region.
[src:service-mesh-deep/proxy-server] Unlike regular residential proxies, which hide the user's real IP address behind another IP address, rotating residential proxies, also known as *backconnect proxies*, conceal the user's real IP address behind a pool of proxies.
[src:service-mesh-deep/proxy-server] These proxies switch between themselves at every session or at regular intervals.
[src:service-mesh-deep/proxy-server] Despite providers' assertions that the proxy hosts are voluntarily participating, numerous proxies are operated on potentially compromised hosts, including Internet of things devices.
[src:service-mesh-deep/proxy-server] Through the process of cross-referencing the hosts, researchers have identified and analyzed logs that have been classified as potentially unwanted program and exposed a range of unauthorized activities conducted by RESIP hosts.
[src:service-mesh-deep/proxy-server] These activities encompassed illegal promotion, fast fluxing, phishing, hosting malware, and more.
[src:service-mesh-deep/service-mesh] In software architecture, a **service mesh** is a dedicated infrastructure layer for facilitating service-to-service communications between services or microservices using a proxy.
[src:service-mesh-deep/service-mesh] A dedicated communication layer can provide numerous benefits, such as providing observability into communications, providing secure connections, and automating retries and backoff for failed requests.
[src:service-mesh-deep/service-mesh] A service mesh consists of network proxies paired with each service in an application and a set of task-management processes.
[src:service-mesh-deep/service-mesh] The proxies are called the data plane and the management processes are called the control plane.
[src:service-mesh-deep/service-mesh] The data plane intercepts calls between different services and processes them; the control plane is the brain of the mesh that coordinates the behavior of proxies and provides APIs for operations and maintenance personnel to manipulate and observe the entire network.
[src:service-mesh-deep/service-mesh] The service mesh architecture is implemented by software products such as Istio, Cilium, Linkerd, Consul, AWS App Mesh, Kuma, Traefik Mesh, and Greymatter.io.
[src:service-mesh-deep/service-mesh] Many service meshes use the Envoy proxy on the data plane.
[src:service-mesh-deep/traffic-management] Istio’s traffic routing rules let you easily control the flow of traffic and API calls between services.
[src:service-mesh-deep/traffic-management] Istio simplifies configuration of service-level properties like circuit breakers, timeouts, and retries, and makes it easy to set up important tasks like A/B testing, canary rollouts, and staged rollouts with percentage-based traffic splits.
[src:service-mesh-deep/traffic-management] It also provides out-of-box reliability features that help make your application more resilient against failures of dependent services or the network.
[src:service-mesh-deep/traffic-management] Istio’s traffic management model relies on the Envoy proxies that are deployed along with your services.
[src:service-mesh-deep/traffic-management] All traffic that your mesh services send and receive (data plane traffic) is proxied through Envoy, making it easy to direct and control traffic around your mesh without making any changes to your services.
[src:service-mesh-deep/traffic-management] If you’re interested in the details of how the features described in this guide work, you can find out more about Istio’s traffic management implementation in the architecture overview.
[src:service-mesh-deep/traffic-management] The rest of this guide introduces Istio’s traffic management features.
[src:service-mesh-deep/traffic-management] In order to direct traffic within your mesh, Istio needs to know where all your endpoints are, and which services they belong to.
[src:service-mesh-deep/traffic-management] To populate its own service registry, Istio connects to a service discovery system.
[src:service-mesh-deep/traffic-management] For example, if you’ve installed Istio on a Kubernetes cluster, then Istio automatically detects the services and endpoints in that cluster.
[src:service-mesh-deep/traffic-management] Using this service registry, the Envoy proxies can then direct traffic to the relevant services.
[src:service-mesh-deep/traffic-management] Most microservice-based applications have multiple instances of each service workload to handle service traffic, sometimes referred to as a load balancing pool.
[src:service-mesh-deep/traffic-management] While Istio’s basic service discovery and load balancing gives you a working service mesh, it’s far from all that Istio can do.
[src:service-mesh-deep/traffic-management] In many cases you might want more fine-grained control over what happens to your mesh traffic.
[src:service-mesh-deep/traffic-management] You might want to direct a particular percentage of traffic to a new version of a service as part of A/B testing, or apply a different load balancing policy to traffic for a particular subset of service instances.
[src:service-mesh-deep/traffic-management] You might also want to apply special rules to traffic coming into or out of your mesh, or add an external dependency of your mesh to the service registry.
[src:service-mesh-deep/traffic-management] You can do all this and more by adding your own traffic configuration to Istio using Istio’s traffic management API.
[src:service-mesh-deep/traffic-management] Like other Istio configuration, the API is specified using Kubernetes custom resource definitions (CRDs), which you can configure using YAML, as you’ll see in the examples.
[src:service-mesh-deep/traffic-management] The rest of this guide examines each of the traffic management API resources and what you can do with them.
[src:service-mesh-deep/traffic-management] This guide also gives an overview of some of the network resilience and testing features that are built in to the API resources.
[src:service-mesh-deep/traffic-management] Virtual services, along with destination rules, are the key building blocks of Istio’s traffic routing functionality.
[src:service-mesh-deep/traffic-management] A virtual service lets you configure how requests are routed to a service within an Istio service mesh, building on the basic connectivity and discovery provided by Istio and your platform.
[src:service-mesh-deep/traffic-management] Each virtual service consists of a set of routing rules that are evaluated in order, letting Istio match each given request to the virtual service to a specific real destination within the mesh.
[src:service-mesh-deep/traffic-management] Your mesh can require multiple virtual services or none depending on your use case.
[src:service-mesh-deep/traffic-management] Virtual services play a key role in making Istio’s traffic management flexible and powerful.
[src:service-mesh-deep/traffic-management] They do this by strongly decoupling where clients send their requests from the destination workloads that actually implement them.
[src:service-mesh-deep/traffic-management] Virtual services also provide a rich way of specifying different traffic routing rules for sending traffic to those workloads.
[src:service-mesh-deep/traffic-management] Without virtual services, Envoy distributes traffic using least requests load balancing between all service instances, as described in the introduction.
[src:service-mesh-deep/traffic-management] You can improve this behavior with what you know about the workloads.
[src:service-mesh-deep/traffic-management] For example, some might represent a different version.
[src:service-mesh-deep/traffic-management] This can be useful in A/B testing, where you might want to configure traffic routes based on percentages across different service versions, or to direct traffic from your internal users to a particular set of instances.
[src:service-mesh-deep/traffic-management] With a virtual service, you can specify traffic behavior for one or more hostnames.
[src:service-mesh-deep/traffic-management] You use routing rules in the virtual service that tell Envoy how to send the virtual service’s traffic to appropriate destinations.
[src:service-mesh-deep/traffic-management] Route destinations can be different versions of the same service or entirely different services.
[src:service-mesh-deep/traffic-management] A typical use case is to send traffic to different versions of a service, specified as service subsets.
[src:service-mesh-deep/traffic-management] Clients send requests to the virtual service host as if it was a single entity, and Envoy then routes the traffic to the different versions depending on the virtual service rules: for example, “20% of calls go to the new version” or “calls from these users go to version 2”.
[src:service-mesh-deep/traffic-management] This allows you to, for instance, create a canary rollout where you gradually increase the percentage of traffic that’s sent to a new service version.
[src:service-mesh-deep/traffic-management] The traffic routing is completely separate from the instance deployment, meaning that the number of instances implementing the new service version can scale up and down based on traffic load without referring to traffic routing at all.
[src:service-mesh-deep/traffic-management] By contrast, container orchestration platforms like Kubernetes only support traffic distribution based on instance scaling, which quickly becomes complex.
[src:service-mesh-deep/traffic-management] You can read more about how virtual services help with canary deployments in Canary Deployments using Istio.
[src:service-mesh-deep/traffic-management] In some cases you also need to configure destination rules to use these features, as these are where you specify your service subsets.
[src:service-mesh-deep/traffic-management] Specifying service subsets and other destination-specific policies in a separate object lets you reuse these cleanly between virtual services.
[src:service-mesh-deep/traffic-management] You can find out more about destination rules in the next section.
[src:service-mesh-deep/traffic-management] The following virtual service routes requests to different versions of a service depending on whether the request comes from a particular user.
[src:service-mesh-deep/traffic-management] The `hosts` field lists the virtual service’s hosts - in other words, the user-addressable destination or destinations that these routing rules apply to.
[src:service-mesh-deep/traffic-management] This is the address or addresses the client uses when sending requests to the service.
[src:service-mesh-deep/traffic-management] The virtual service hostname can be an IP address, a DNS name, or, depending on the platform, a short name (such as a Kubernetes service short name) that resolves, implicitly or explicitly, to a fully qualified domain name (FQDN).
[src:service-mesh-deep/traffic-management] You can also use wildcard ("*") prefixes, letting you create a single set of routing rules for all matching services.
[src:service-mesh-deep/traffic-management] Virtual service hosts don’t actually have to be part of the Istio service registry, they are simply virtual destinations.
[src:service-mesh-deep/traffic-management] This lets you model traffic for virtual hosts that don’t have routable entries inside the mesh.
[src:service-mesh-deep/traffic-management] A routing rule consists of the destination where you want the traffic to go and zero or more match conditions, depending on your use case.
[src:service-mesh-deep/traffic-management] The first routing rule in the example has a condition and so begins with the `match` field.
[src:service-mesh-deep/traffic-management] In this case you want this routing to apply to all requests from the user “jason”, so you use the `headers`, `end-user`, and `exact` fields to select the appropriate requests.
[src:service-mesh-deep/traffic-management] The route section’s `destination` field specifies the actual destination for traffic that matches this condition.
[src:service-mesh-deep/traffic-management] Unlike the virtual service’s host(s), the destination’s host must be a real destination that exists in Istio’s service registry or Envoy won’t know where to send traffic to it.
[src:service-mesh-deep/traffic-management] This can be a mesh service with proxies or a non-mesh service added using a service entry.
[src:service-mesh-deep/traffic-management] Note in this and the other examples on this page, we use a Kubernetes short name for the destination hosts for simplicity.
[src:service-mesh-deep/traffic-management] When this rule is evaluated, Istio adds a domain suffix based on the namespace of the virtual service that contains the routing rule to get the fully qualified name for the host.
[src:service-mesh-deep/traffic-management] Using short names in our examples also means that you can copy and try them in any namespace you like.
[src:service-mesh-deep/traffic-management] The destination section also specifies which subset of this Kubernetes service you want requests that match this rule’s conditions to go to, in this case the subset named v2.
[src:service-mesh-deep/traffic-management] You’ll see how you define a service subset in the section on destination rules below.
[src:service-mesh-deep/traffic-management] Routing rules are **evaluated in sequential order from top to bottom**, with the first rule in the virtual service definition being given highest priority.
[src:service-mesh-deep/traffic-management] In this case you want anything that doesn’t match the first routing rule to go to a default destination, specified in the second rule.
[src:service-mesh-deep/traffic-management] Because of this, the second rule has no match conditions and just directs traffic to the v3 subset.
[src:service-mesh-deep/traffic-management] We recommend providing a default “no condition” or weight-based rule (described below) like this as the last rule in each virtual service to ensure that traffic to the virtual service always has at least one matching route.
[src:service-mesh-deep/traffic-management] As you saw above, routing rules are a powerful tool for routing particular subsets of traffic to particular destinations.
[src:service-mesh-deep/traffic-management] You can set match conditions on traffic ports, header fields, URIs, and more.
[src:service-mesh-deep/traffic-management] For example, this virtual service lets users send traffic to two separate services, ratings and reviews, as if they were part of a bigger virtual service at `http://bookinfo.com/.` The virtual service rules match traffic based on request URIs and direct requests to the appropriate service.
[src:service-mesh-deep/traffic-management] For some match conditions, you can also choose to select them using the exact value, a prefix, or a regex.
[src:service-mesh-deep/traffic-management] You can add multiple match conditions to the same `match` block to AND your conditions, or add multiple match blocks to the same rule to OR your conditions.
[src:service-mesh-deep/traffic-management] You can also have multiple routing rules for any given virtual service.
[src:service-mesh-deep/traffic-management] This lets you make your routing conditions as complex or simple as you like within a single virtual service.
[src:service-mesh-deep/traffic-management] A full list of match condition fields and their possible values can be found in the `HTTPMatchRequest` reference.
[src:service-mesh-deep/traffic-management] In addition to using match conditions, you can distribute traffic by percentage “weight”.
[src:service-mesh-deep/traffic-management] To learn more about the actions available, see the `HTTPRoute` reference.
[src:service-mesh-deep/traffic-management] Along with virtual services, destination rules are a key part of Istio’s traffic routing functionality.
[src:service-mesh-deep/traffic-management] You can think of virtual services as how you route your traffic **to** a given destination, and then you use destination rules to configure what happens to traffic **for** that destination.
[src:service-mesh-deep/traffic-management] Destination rules are applied after virtual service routing rules are evaluated, so they apply to the traffic’s “real” destination.
[src:service-mesh-deep/traffic-management] In particular, you use destination rules to specify named service subsets, such as grouping all a given service’s instances by version.
[src:service-mesh-deep/traffic-management] You can then use these service subsets in the routing rules of virtual services to control the traffic to different instances of your services.
[src:service-mesh-deep/traffic-management] Destination rules also let you customize Envoy’s traffic policies when calling the entire destination service or a particular service subset, such as your preferred load balancing model, TLS security mode, or circuit breaker settings.
[src:service-mesh-deep/traffic-management] You can see a complete list of destination rule options in the Destination Rule reference.
[src:service-mesh-deep/traffic-management] By default, Istio uses a least requests load balancing policy, where requests are distributed among the instances with the least number of requests.
[src:service-mesh-deep/traffic-management] Istio also supports the following models, which you can specify in destination rules for requests to a particular service or service subset.
[src:service-mesh-deep/traffic-management] See the Envoy load balancing documentation for more information about each option.
[src:service-mesh-deep/traffic-management] Each subset is defined based on one or more `labels`, which in Kubernetes are key/value pairs that are attached to objects such as Pods.
[src:service-mesh-deep/traffic-management] These labels are applied in the Kubernetes service’s deployment as `metadata` to identify different versions.
[src:service-mesh-deep/traffic-management] As well as defining subsets, this destination rule has both a default traffic policy for all subsets in this destination and a subset-specific policy that overrides it for just that subset.
[src:service-mesh-deep/traffic-management] The default policy, defined above the `subsets` field, sets a simple random load balancer for the `v1` and `v3` subsets.
[src:service-mesh-deep/traffic-management] In the `v2` policy, a round-robin load balancer is specified in the corresponding subset’s field.
[src:service-mesh-deep/traffic-management] You use a gateway to manage inbound and outbound traffic for your mesh, letting you specify which traffic you want to enter or leave the mesh.
[src:service-mesh-deep/traffic-management] Gateway configurations are applied to standalone Envoy proxies that are running at the edge of the mesh, rather than sidecar Envoy proxies running alongside your service workloads.
[src:service-mesh-deep/traffic-management] Unlike other mechanisms for controlling traffic entering your systems, such as the Kubernetes Ingress APIs, Istio gateways let you use the full power and flexibility of Istio’s traffic routing.
[src:service-mesh-deep/traffic-management] You can do this because Istio’s Gateway resource just lets you configure layer 4-6 load balancing properties such as ports to expose, TLS settings, and so on.
[src:service-mesh-deep/traffic-management] Then instead of adding application-layer traffic routing (L7) to the same API resource, you bind a regular Istio virtual service to the gateway.
[src:service-mesh-deep/traffic-management] This lets you basically manage gateway traffic like any other data plane traffic in an Istio mesh.
[src:service-mesh-deep/traffic-management] Gateways are primarily used to manage ingress traffic, but you can also configure egress gateways.
[src:service-mesh-deep/traffic-management] An egress gateway lets you configure a dedicated exit node for the traffic leaving the mesh, letting you limit which services can or should access external networks, or to enable secure control of egress traffic to add security to your mesh, for example.
[src:service-mesh-deep/traffic-management] You can also use a gateway to configure a purely internal proxy.
[src:service-mesh-deep/traffic-management] Istio provides some preconfigured gateway proxy deployments (`istio-ingressgateway` and `istio-egressgateway`) that you can use - both are deployed if you use our demo installation, while just the ingress gateway is deployed with our default profile.
[src:service-mesh-deep/traffic-management] You can apply your own gateway configurations to these deployments or deploy and configure your own gateway proxies.
[src:service-mesh-deep/traffic-management] This gateway configuration lets HTTPS traffic from `ext-host.example.com` into the mesh on port 443, but doesn’t specify any routing for the traffic.
[src:service-mesh-deep/traffic-management] To specify routing and for the gateway to work as intended, you must also bind the gateway to a virtual service.
[src:service-mesh-deep/traffic-management] You can then configure the virtual service with routing rules for the external traffic.
[src:service-mesh-deep/traffic-management] You use a service entry to add an entry to the service registry that Istio maintains internally.
[src:service-mesh-deep/traffic-management] After you add the service entry, the Envoy proxies can send traffic to the service as if it was a service in your mesh.
[src:service-mesh-deep/traffic-management] You don’t need to add a service entry for every external service that you want your mesh services to use.
[src:service-mesh-deep/traffic-management] By default, Istio configures the Envoy proxies to passthrough requests to unknown services.
[src:service-mesh-deep/traffic-management] However, you can’t use Istio features to control the traffic to destinations that aren’t registered in the mesh.
[src:service-mesh-deep/traffic-management] You specify the external resource using the `hosts` field.
[src:service-mesh-deep/traffic-management] You can qualify it fully or use a wildcard prefixed domain name.
[src:service-mesh-deep/traffic-management] You can configure virtual services and destination rules to control traffic to a service entry in a more granular way, in the same way you configure traffic for any other service in the mesh.
[src:service-mesh-deep/traffic-management] See the Service Entry reference for more possible configuration options.
[src:service-mesh-deep/traffic-management] By default, Istio configures every Envoy proxy to accept traffic on all the ports of its associated workload, and to reach every workload in the mesh when forwarding traffic.
[src:service-mesh-deep/traffic-management] You might want to limit sidecar reachability like this in larger applications, where having every proxy configured to reach every other service in the mesh can potentially affect mesh performance due to high memory usage.
[src:service-mesh-deep/traffic-management] You can specify that you want a sidecar configuration to apply to all workloads in a particular namespace, or choose specific workloads using a `workloadSelector`.
[src:service-mesh-deep/traffic-management] See the Sidecar reference for more details.
[src:service-mesh-deep/traffic-management] As well as helping you direct traffic around your mesh, Istio provides opt-in failure recovery and fault injection features that you can configure dynamically at runtime.
[src:service-mesh-deep/traffic-management] Using these features helps your applications operate reliably, ensuring that the service mesh can tolerate failing nodes and preventing localized failures from cascading to other nodes.
[src:service-mesh-deep/traffic-management] A timeout is the amount of time that an Envoy proxy should wait for replies from a given service, ensuring that services don’t hang around waiting for replies indefinitely and that calls succeed or fail within a predictable timeframe.
[src:service-mesh-deep/traffic-management] The Envoy timeout for HTTP requests is disabled in Istio by default.
[src:service-mesh-deep/traffic-management] For some applications and services, Istio’s default timeout might not be appropriate.
[src:service-mesh-deep/traffic-management] For example, a timeout that is too long could result in excessive latency from waiting for replies from failing services, while a timeout that is too short could result in calls failing unnecessarily while waiting for an operation involving multiple services to return.
[src:service-mesh-deep/traffic-management] To find and use your optimal timeout settings, Istio lets you easily adjust timeouts dynamically on a per-service basis using virtual services without having to edit your service code.
[src:service-mesh-deep/traffic-management] A retry setting specifies the maximum number of times an Envoy proxy attempts to connect to a service if the initial call fails.
[src:service-mesh-deep/traffic-management] Retries can enhance service availability and application performance by making sure that calls don’t fail permanently because of transient problems such as a temporarily overloaded service or network.
[src:service-mesh-deep/traffic-management] The interval between retries (25ms+) is variable and determined automatically by Istio, preventing the called service from being overwhelmed with requests.
[src:service-mesh-deep/traffic-management] The default retry behavior for HTTP requests is to retry twice before returning the error.
[src:service-mesh-deep/traffic-management] Like timeouts, Istio’s default retry behavior might not suit your application needs in terms of latency (too many retries to a failed service can slow things down) or availability.
[src:service-mesh-deep/traffic-management] Also like timeouts, you can adjust your retry settings on a per-service basis in virtual services without having to touch your service code.
[src:service-mesh-deep/traffic-management] You can also further refine your retry behavior by adding per-retry timeouts, specifying the amount of time you want to wait for each retry attempt to successfully connect to the service.
[src:service-mesh-deep/traffic-management] The following example configures a maximum of 3 retries to connect to this service subset after an initial call failure, each with a 2 second timeout.
[src:service-mesh-deep/traffic-management] Circuit breakers are another useful mechanism Istio provides for creating resilient microservice-based applications.
[src:service-mesh-deep/traffic-management] In a circuit breaker, you set limits for calls to individual hosts within a service, such as the number of concurrent connections or how many times calls to this host have failed.
[src:service-mesh-deep/traffic-management] Once that limit has been reached the circuit breaker “trips” and stops further connections to that host.
[src:service-mesh-deep/traffic-management] Using a circuit breaker pattern enables fast failure rather than clients trying to connect to an overloaded or failing host.
[src:service-mesh-deep/traffic-management] As circuit breaking applies to “real” mesh destinations in a load balancing pool, you configure circuit breaker thresholds in destination rules, with the settings applying to each individual host in the service.
[src:service-mesh-deep/traffic-management] You can find out more about creating circuit breakers in Circuit Breaking.
[src:service-mesh-deep/traffic-management] After you’ve configured your network, including failure recovery policies, you can use Istio’s fault injection mechanisms to test the failure recovery capacity of your application as a whole.
[src:service-mesh-deep/traffic-management] Fault injection is a testing method that introduces errors into a system to ensure that it can withstand and recover from error conditions.
[src:service-mesh-deep/traffic-management] Using fault injection can be particularly useful to ensure that your failure recovery policies aren’t incompatible or too restrictive, potentially resulting in critical services being unavailable.
[src:service-mesh-deep/traffic-management] Unlike other mechanisms for introducing errors, such as delaying packets or killing pods at the network layer, Istio lets you inject faults at the application layer.
[src:service-mesh-deep/traffic-management] This lets you inject more relevant failures, such as HTTP error codes, to get more relevant results.
[src:service-mesh-deep/traffic-management] For example, this virtual service introduces a 5 second delay for 1 out of every 1000 requests to the `ratings` service.
[src:service-mesh-deep/traffic-management] For detailed instructions on how to configure delays and aborts, see Fault Injection.
[src:service-mesh-deep/traffic-management] Istio failure recovery features are completely transparent to the application.
[src:service-mesh-deep/traffic-management] Applications don’t know if an Envoy sidecar proxy is handling failures for a called service before returning a response.
[src:service-mesh-deep/traffic-management] This means that if you are also setting failure recovery policies in your application code you need to keep in mind that both work independently, and therefore might conflict.
[src:service-mesh-deep/traffic-management] For example, suppose you can have two timeouts, one configured in a virtual service and another in the application.
[src:service-mesh-deep/traffic-management] The application sets a 2 second timeout for an API call to a service.
[src:service-mesh-deep/traffic-management] However, you configured a 3 second timeout with 1 retry in your virtual service.
[src:service-mesh-deep/traffic-management] In this case, the application’s timeout kicks in first, so your Envoy timeout and retry attempt has no effect.
[src:service-mesh-deep/traffic-management] While Istio failure recovery features improve the reliability and availability of services in the mesh, applications must handle the failure or errors and take appropriate fallback actions.
[src:service-mesh-deep/traffic-management] For example, when all instances in a load balancing pool have failed, Envoy returns an `HTTP 503` code.
[src:service-mesh-deep/traffic-management] The application must implement any fallback logic needed to handle the `HTTP 503` error code.
